Read and internalize @soul.md before writing any code in this project.

Every prompt, label, color choice, animation, copy string, and architectural decision must reflect the five principles defined there:

1. Name the unnamed — give the user the word for what they felt
2. Silence is information — a quiet screen means the speaker is being straight
3. The speaker deserves fairness — always generate the steelman
4. Truth is a trajectory, not a verdict — the line, not a switch
5. Respect every glance — every element earns its presence or gets cut

When writing LLM prompts: analytical not adversarial, precise language ("unsupported" not "false"), treat every argument as a sincere attempt at reasoning.

When writing UI copy: flags describe what happened not what the speaker is, loading states are calm, empty states invite.

When choosing colors: red = "pay attention here", green = "this checks out", amber = "worth a closer look". Animations fire only on state changes.
